@NODE "introduction" "WBTicTacToe - Introduction"

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

WBTicTacToe is a take on the basic Tic-Tac-Toe / 3-in-a-row / noughts and crosses game, which adds some more interesting possibilities to the game. It allows for boards up to 5 squares wide, and boards with 3 or 4 dimensions. 3 dimensional boards allow straight lines in any direction, even diagonally up and down. 4 dimensional boards also allow straight lines across the board at different timepoints. This means there are many more possible moves than the classic 3x3 (though of course you can play that size too).

It can be played by two players or one player can play against a CPU player with three levels of difficulty.

This is a complete rewrite of an old game I wrote many years ago and recently rediscovered. The old version had no AI player and the graphics weren't very good at all, and it doesn't work on newer machines. This version includes AI, better graphics, and support for graphics cards as well as native screens - high colour screens will automatically get much nicer player markers.

For those unfamiliar with the original, TicTacToe is an old game usually played with a pen and paper, in which players take it in turn to put a mark in one square of a 3x3 grid, with the aim of trying to get three of their marks in a row. Once you grasp the concept of the game however, the board that size means it's almost impossible to lose. Most games simply end in a draw. This version makes things more interesting by introducing more squares on the board, and adding up to two extra dimensions to the board, so you can play on the classic 3x3 board, a 3x3x3 board, or even a 3x3x3x3 board!

@{"Read more about how to play WBTicTacToe" LINK "playing"}

