@NODE "playing" "WBTicTacToe - Playing"

@{b}Starting WBTicTacToe@{ub}

Just run the game and you'll be presented with a 3x3 board in 2-player mode, ready to go.

@{b}Playing@{ub}

Player 1 always goes first. If playing against a CPU player, the human player is always player 1. The current player will have their coloured marker at the top of the window highlighted.

To put your marker in any empty square, just click in the square. Your marker is placed in the square and play then passes on to the next player. The first player to get a complete, straight row of their markers across the board in any direction is the winner, and the winning markers will be highlighted.

Playing with three dimensions means that, as well as getting a full row across the board, you can also win by completing a row from top to bottom, either straight down or diagonally from corner to corner.

Playing with four dimensions allows you to complete a full row across a number of different time slots, as well as the other methods for the first three dimensions. Again, these rows through time can be straight (i.e., the same square in each time slot), or diagonally.

@{b}The Main Window@{ub}
The main window has each player's markers at the top - Player 1 on the left is red and Player 2 on the right is green. The current player's marker is highlighted during their turn. In the centre at the top is a cycle gadget which is used to select which time's board is displayed in a four dimensional game. It is disabled for games not using four dimensions.

@{b}Menus@{ub}

The menus of the game window can be used for changing the settings of the game. The following settings are available:

 - Board Menu: This controls the size of the board.
   - Dimensions: Choose from 2, 3 or 4 dimensions. 2 dimensions is the traditional, flat board. 3 dimensions introduces the vertical element, and 4 dimensions brings time into play. Defaults to 2.
   - Size: This sets the size of each side of the board, and the number of counters required in a full row to win. The options are 3, 4 or 5. This size applies to all dimensions currently used. Defaults to 3.

 - Opponent: This menu chooses who your opponent is.
  - Human: Play against another person.
  - CPU (Easy): Play against an AI player with basic skills.
  - CPU (Medium): Play against an AI player which makes better decisions based on the current board.
  - CPU (Difficult): Play against an AI player which makes complicated decisions based on your moves, and which looks for a number of different strategies and patterns.

- Time: This menu controls the use of time in four dimensional games. It has no effect on 2D or 3D games.
  - Still: Time is stopped, and the Time cycle gadget must be used to move from one time's board to another.
  - Slow: The boards are swapped once every few seconds.
  - Medium: The boards are swapped a big more frequently.
  - Fast: The boards are swapped every 1-2 seconds.

Changing a setting that changes the nature of the game (board size, dimensions, opponent) will reset the game. If there's a game in progress you'll be warned and given the opportunity to cancel and carry on with the existing game instead of resetting.

In addition, there is also a Game menu:
  - New: Resets the current game
  - About: Opens an About requester
  - Quit: Quits WBTicTacToe. A warning will be given if there's a game currently being played.

